 from North Africa or, more often, a nickname for someone thought to resemble a Moor. Compare   Morrell   and   Moreau  .","English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>More</i> (Old French <i>More</i>, <i>Maur</i>, Latin <i>Maurus</i>), originally denoting either ‘Moor’ or someone with a swarthy complexion (compare   Morrell  ,   Morrin  ,   Morris  , and sense 2 above). There was a 6th-century Christian saint of this name."]},{"name":"Moree","meanings":["Altered form of   Morey  .","French (<b>Morée</b>): habitational name from a place so named in Loir-et-Cher."]},{"name":"Morie","meanings":["Altered form of <b>Moree</b>, itself perhaps an altered form of English or French   Morey   (compare 2 below) or of Irish   Morrow  .","English (London): variant of   Morey  . This surname is rare in Britain.","French: unexplained. This surname is rare in France."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Moray was born about 1372, in Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Henry Sutherland Lord Torboll in 1402, in Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1438, at the age of 68, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"Abt 1372–Abt 1438":"umbes 1372–umbes 1438","1362–1434":"1362–1434","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1372–1438":"1372–1438","about 1480":"umbes 1480","Abt 1372":"umbes 1372","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1434":"1434","1362":"1362","Abt 1434":"umbes 1434","1372":"1372","1482":"1482","Abt 1438":"umbes 1438","1438":"1438","Southerland, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Duffus Castle, Morayshire, Scotland":"Duffus, Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1372–Abt 1438":"noin 1372–noin 1438","1362–1434":"